Mathematics as Relationship

Your statement

“Math is the language of faith and connection.”

can be interpreted in a way that is both poetic and mathematically grounded.

I’d phrase it slightly differently:

Mathematics is a language for expressing relationships and constraints with unusual precision.

Faith, in many traditions, concerns trust, commitment, coherence, and unseen realities. Mathematics doesn’t prove or replace faith, but it provides a language for describing relational structures. That’s one reason mathematics transfers so well across physics, engineering, economics, and computer science: it captures patterns that are independent of any single application.

